      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "b109374b0690234a",
      "text": "[...] The victims were played off against each other and robbed of their humanity. Anyone who wanted to survive became a threat and the enemy of all those who were not yet definitively doomed to die and who initially believed themselves to be uninvolved. The rational credo mercifully relieved both the victims and the uninvolved of the accusation of immorality and feelings of [[Guilt]]. The calculation of self-preservation reduced human life and robbed it of its humanity."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7184de5d294359d0",
      "text": "The Nazi regime has long been overcome, but to this day we still suffer from the symptoms of poisoning it triggered. If we think of the chronic inability to take the relevance of the [[Holocaust]] seriously and to really see through the system of mass murder, if we think of our willingness to continue to play the game of history with the prepared dice of rationality, namely by dismissing ethical questions from the outset as irrelevant and cranky and brushing them aside with the argument of a lack of purpose – then we would have to recognize the extent of the corruption that the Holocaust brought glaringly to light without even coming close to describing it."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "063572fb606ae936",
      "text": "In my (Bauman) earliest childhood, my grandfather tried for two years, relatively unsuccessfully, to get me interested in the ideas and images of the Bible. He may not have been a particularly good teacher, or I may have been a stubborn, ungrateful pupil, but I remember almost nothing of that time. But there is one story that is deeply imprinted in my mind and that occupied me for many years: a pious old man, traveling with a donkey loaded with sacks of food, meets a beggar on the street. The beggar asks for something to eat. \"Wait,\" says the old man, \"until I have untied the sacks.\" But before he could do so, the beggar was overcome by hunger and sank to the ground, dead. Then the old man prayed and said: \"Punish me, O Lord, for I have failed to save the life of my fellow man!\" The deep disturbance this story caused me is the only memory I have of my grandfather's many moral sermons. It contradicted everything I was ever taught at school. The story seemed illogical to me (and it was) and therefore wrong (but it wasn't). Only the Holocaust made me painfully aware that the second statement does not necessarily follow from the first."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "98c4b6251c553d64",
      "text": "218–219"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "fe2daea498bd4769",
      "text": "Even if it is certain that not much more could have been done concretely to save the victims of the Holocaust (or only at an outrageous price), this does not mean that the moral conflict is over. It is normal for a morally awake person to feel [[Shame]] (even if it must appear irrational in view of the compulsion for self-preservation). This feeling of shame is the indispensable prerequisite for becoming immune to the creeping poison and the malignant long-term effects of the Holocaust; no attempt, however meticulous and historically correct, to calculate who could have helped and who could not, or \"who could still be helped\" and who could not, will change anything about this shame."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7d641004bbe944bd",
      "text": "Not even the most precise quantitative methods for researching the \"facts of the case\" can provide an objective (i.e. universally binding) solution to the problem of moral responsibility. There is no scientific method with which it could be determined whether the non-Jewish neighbors allowed the deportation of the Jews to happen because the Jews were so passive and compliant, or whether the Jews did not escape their persecutors because they reacted to the hostility or indifference of their surroundings and did not even make the attempt. Nor is it possible to scientifically determine whether the wealthier inmates of the Warsaw ghetto could have alleviated the fate of those dying of hunger and cold, whether the German Jews could have done something about the deportation of the Eastern Jews* Ostjuden or whether the Jews with French passports could at least have made the internment of the \"non-French Jews\" more difficult. And what is even worse: the quantification of objective possibilities and the offsetting of the price obscures the moral core of the problem."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "424971e6e28706fa",
      "text": "The question is not whether those who survived rightly feel shame or pride. Be it that they actively resisted or had to watch helplessly, be it that they behaved passively and had to fear becoming victims themselves. The decisive factor is that the feeling of shame sets us free and is the only way to learn to understand the moral lesson of the Holocaust and to banish the spectre of this terrible historical experience, which still burdens us to this day and leads us to neglect vigilance in order to be able to live in peace with the past. The alternative is not shame or pride. The alternative is pride in feeling morally purifying shame, or shame in feeling morally devastating pride. I don't know how I would have reacted if a stranger had come to my door asking for protection, putting my life and that of my family in danger. I was spared such a [[Decision-Making]] situation."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "0af430da373c0c93",
      "text": "219–220"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "90a8dfc92c023d59",
      "text": "Certainly I could have rationally justified my rejection to myself and others by taking stock of the lives saved and sacrificed. But it is also certain that I would have felt an illogical but essentially human [[Shame]] that is difficult to explain. And I am also sure that without this feeling of shame, the decision to send the stranger on would corrupt me for the rest of my life.\nThe order established by a murderous totalitarian state dehumanized the victims and those who passively watched the persecution by imposing the logic of self-preservation on both as an excuse for moral indifference and passivity. No one who collapsed under the weight of this pressure should be found guilty. On the other hand, no one should be spared the agony of moral self-loathing for this reason. Only those who feel shame for their own failures can break through the walls of the mental prison that has outlasted its designers and overseers. Our task is to finally destroy the power of dictatorial state terror over the victims and the passive, which continues to this day.\nThe Holocaust is shrinking more and more into a historical episode. The lesson we have to learn from it can be less and less limited to calling those responsible to account or seeking restitution. The criminals who have not yet been brought to justice are now - like many of the survivors - of advanced age. And even if the one or other mass murderer is still tracked down and brought to his belated trial, it is harder and harder to do justice to the monstrosity of the crime with a dignified trial (the embarrassment of the trials against Demianiuk and Barbie are an example). There are also not many people still alive who were old enough at the time of the Holocaust to decide whether or not they wanted to help a stranger. If the historical significance of the Holocaust were to be settled with atoning for and compensating for the injustice committed, one could say that it would be in the best hands of historians as a heinous piece of the past. However, atonement and retribution are not sufficient reasons for never forgetting the Holocaust - this is becoming increasingly clear as we see that the practical relevance of the Holocaust is becoming noticeably less important.\nToday, the Holocaust is less than ever a private matter for prosecutors or direct victims who expect our sympathy, help or concessions; the Holocaust does not only concern the eyewitnesses who struggle for forgiveness or proof of their innocence."
    },
    {
      "type": "pagefold",
      "id": "ec438335a7429f3f",
      "text": "220–221"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "df6f3a27bc322275",
      "text": "The current significance of the Holocaust lies in the message it contains for humanity.\nThe Holocaust has shown us how quickly people who are forced into a situation in which there are no more good decisions, or in which the price for good decisions is infinitely high, suppress the question of moral obligation or do not even ask it in the first place and instead submit themselves entirely to the dictates of rational interest and self-preservation. In any system in which rationality and ethics point in opposite directions, humanity falls by the wayside. Evil can now take its course unhindered and build on the fact that people normally refrain from spontaneous, reckless action - and resistance to evil is, after all, reckless and spontaneous. Evil does not need fanatical followers or an enthusiastic audience. The instinct for self-preservation alone is enough, if it is nourished by the comforting thought that it is not yet one's turn and that one can possibly save oneself through passivity.\nThe Holocaust holds another equally important lesson: while the first is a warning, the second offers hope. Because of the second, however, the first cannot be repeated often enough.\nThe second lesson says that the instinct of self-preservation does not necessarily defeat moral duty. One can be urged to do so, but not forced to do so, so that the responsibility cannot be shifted to those who exert the pressure. It does not matter how many people put moral responsibility above the rationality of self-preservation - what matters is that some did. The fact that a few resisted invalidates the logic of self-preservation and proves that there are always choices. The question is how many must resist the logic of evil in order to destroy it. Is there a certain threshold of disobedience at which the technology of evil fails?"
