      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "424971e6e28706fa",
        "text": "The question is not whether those who survived rightly feel shame or pride. Be it that they actively resisted or had to watch helplessly, be it that they behaved passively and had to fear becoming victims themselves. The decisive factor is that the feeling of shame sets us free and is the only way to learn to understand the moral lesson of the Holocaust and to banish the spectre of this terrible historical experience, which still burdens us to this day and leads us to neglect vigilance in order to be able to live in peace with the past. The alternative is not shame or pride. The alternative is pride in feeling morally purifying shame, or shame in feeling morally devastating pride. I don't know how I would have reacted if a stranger had come to my door asking for protection, putting my life and that of my family in danger. I was spared such a decision-making situation."
