      "type": "edit",
      "id": "df6f3a27bc322275",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "df6f3a27bc322275",
        "text": "The current significance of the Holocaust lies in the message it contains for humanity.\nThe Holocaust has shown us how quickly people who are forced into a situation in which there are no more good decisions, or in which the price for good decisions is infinitely high, suppress the question of moral obligation or do not even ask it in the first place and instead submit themselves entirely to the dictates of rational interest and self-preservation. In any system in which rationality and ethics point in opposite directions, humanity falls by the wayside. Evil can now take its course unhindered and build on the fact that people normally refrain from spontaneous, reckless action - and resistance to evil is, after all, reckless and spontaneous. Evil does not need fanatical followers or an enthusiastic audience. The instinct for self-preservation alone is enough, if it is nourished by the comforting thought that it is not yet one's turn and that one can possibly save oneself through passivity.\nThe Holocaust holds another equally important lesson: while the first is a warning, the second offers hope. Because of the second, however, the first cannot be repeated often enough.\nThe second lesson says that the instinct of self-preservation does not necessarily defeat moral duty. One can be urged to do so, but not forced to do so, so that the responsibility cannot be shifted to those who exert the pressure. It does not matter how many people put moral responsibility above the rationality of self-preservation - what matters is that some did. The fact that a few resisted invalidates the logic of self-preservation and proves that there are always choices. The question is how many must resist the logic of evil in order to destroy it. Is there a certain threshold of disobedience at which the technology of evil fails?\n Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
